1 Task 1: Data Source

I got the NHANES 2013-2014 dataset (Demographics and Questionnaire on Reproductive Health) from the links below. - https://wwwn.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/search/datapage.aspx?Component=Demographics&CycleBeginYear=2013 - https://wwwn.cdc.gov/Nchs/Nhanes/2013-2014/RHQ_H.htm The data was gathered the National Center for Health Statistics (NCHS), Division of Health and Nutrition Examination Surveys (DHANES), part of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) during 2013 and 2014. It was conducted throughout America in order to monitor the U.S. distribution of population, diseases, risk factors, and diet, etc. Also, NHANES claims that it uses a complex, multistage, probability sampling design. For example, different races are weighed differently.

4 Task 4: Code Book

Variable Type Details

tried binary Tried for a year to get pregnant: 1(yes/14%), 0(no/86%)
csec quantitative The number of C-section(s) the subject had (0-4) / 260 missing values
bcpills binary Ever taken birth control pills: 1(yes/81%), 2(no/19%)
race multi-categorical Race: 1(Mexican American), 2(Other Hispanic), 3(Non-Hispanic White), 4(Non-Hispanic Black), 5(Others)
edu multi-categorical Educational level: 1(Less than 9th grade), 2(9-11th grade), 3(high school graduate/GED), 4(some college or AA degree), 4(higher) / 6 missing values
married binary 1(currently married/52%) 2(not currently married/48%) / 6 missing values
famsize quantitative Number of the family size (1-7)
agefirst quantitative Age when first menstrual period occurred (8-22)

5 Task 5: My Subjects

The subjects are the women who lived in America and answered to NHANES “Reproductive Health” questionnaires in the term of 2013 and 2014. The questionnaire “Reproductive Health” data originally included 3618 rows. Selecting only those rows with complete answers for my two outcome variables, agemeno and tried reduced the sample size down to 550 rows. Removing a few rows indicating “refused to answer” and “don’t know” in edu, married and agefirst removed 8 more rows. I did not do anything about the purely missing values in predictors.

6 Task 6: My Variables

  • The variable subject is a quantitative variable that would not be in the model itself. It is the subject identification code. It ranges from 73566 to 83689.
  • agemeno is a quantitative variable for the age at the subject’s last menstrual period. It ranges from 17 to 56.
  • tried is a binary variable that indicates if the subject has tried a year to become pregnant. 1 (Yes) is 14% of the dataset and 2 (No) is 86%.
  • csec is a quantitative variable that indicates the number of C-section(s) the subject has had. It ranges from 0 to 4.
  • bcpills is a binary variable to indicate if the subject has ever taken birth control pills. 1 (Yes) is 81% of the dataset and 2 (No) is 19%.
  • race, a multi-categorical variable, indicates the subject’s race.
  • edu is a multi-categorical variable to indicate the subject’s educational level.
  • married is a binary variable to indicate if the subject is currently married (1=yes, 52%) or not (2=no, 48%).
  • famsize is a quantitative variable to indicate the family size of the subject, and it ranges 1 to 7.

  • agefirst is a quantitative variable that indicates the age when the subject’s first menstrual period occurred. It ranges from 8 to 22.

  • csec has 260 missing values, and edu and married have 6 missing values each.

7 Task 7: My Planned Linear Regression Model

  • The quantitative outcome would be agemeno, the age of last menstrual period, which is the point of getting the menopause.
  • The predictors will be bcpills, csec, race, edu, married, famsize, and agefirst.

8 Task 8: My Planned Logistic Regression Model

  • The binary outcome would be tried.
  • the predictors will be the same as the linear regression: bcpills, csec, race, edu, married, famsize and agefirst.

9 Task 9: Affirmation

My dataset meets all the requirements specified in the project instructions. The sample size is in the range of 100 and 1000, and I have a multicategorical variable and a quantitative variable.

# Next calculate bias-corrected AIC
# recall n = 542, and we have 3 models
# so that's 2-4 coefficients to fit

rs$aic.corr <- 542*log(rs$rss / 542) + 2*(2:4) +
               (2 * (2:4) * ((2:4)+1) / (542 - (2:4) - 1))

# Bias-Corrected AIC plot with arrow included
# to indicate minimum AIC-corrected
m2 <- min(rs$aic.corr)
m1 <- which.min(rs$aic.corr)
plot(rs$aic.corr ~ I(2:4), ylab="Bias-Corrected AIC", 
     xlab="# of Fitted Coefficients", pch=16, cex=1.5, 
     col="tomato", main="Bias-Corrected AIC")
arrows(m1+1, m2+3, m1+1, m2+1)

# plot BIC with indicating arrow for minimizer

               data = reproduct, family = binomial(link = logit))
prob <- predict(model.1, data = na.omit(reproduct), type="response")
pred <- prediction(prob, na.omit(reproduct)$tried)
# rest of this doesn't need much adjustment except for titles
perf <- performance(pred, measure = "tpr", x.measure = "fpr")
auc <- performance(pred, measure="auc")
auc <- round(auc@y.values[[1]],3)
roc.data <- data.frame(fpr=unlist(perf@x.values),
                       tpr=unlist(perf@y.values),
                       model="GLM")
ggplot(roc.data, aes(x=fpr, ymin=0, ymax=tpr)) +
    geom_ribbon(alpha=0.2) +
    geom_line(aes(y=tpr)) +
    labs(title = paste0("ROC Curve w/ AUC=", auc),
         subtitle = "Model 1 for reproduct data")
